{"parse":{"title":"Cosmic Hunt","pageid":52588951,"revid":808567141,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>Cosmic Hunt</b> is an old and widely distributed family of cognate myths. They are stories about a large animal that is pursued by hunters, is wounded, and is transformed into a <a href=\"/wiki/Constellation\" title=\"Constellation\">constellation</a>. Variants of the Cosmic Hunt are common in cultures of Northern Eurasia and the Americas, and include the story of <a href=\"/wiki/Callisto_(mythology)\" title=\"Callisto (mythology)\">Callisto</a> in classical sources.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SciAm_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SciAm-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The prey animal is either a <a href=\"/wiki/Bear\" title=\"Bear\">bear</a> or an <a href=\"/wiki/Ungulate\" title=\"Ungulate\">ungulate</a>, and the constellation it is transformed into is typically the four stars of the bowl in the <a href=\"/wiki/Big_Dipper\" title=\"Big Dipper\">Big Dipper</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Asterism_(astronomy)\" title=\"Asterism (astronomy)\">asterism</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Ursa_Major\" title=\"Ursa Major\">Ursa Major</a>. In some variants blood or grease may fall from the wounded animal, in an <a href=\"/wiki/Iroquois\" title=\"Iroquois\">Iroquois</a> version the blood causes leaves to change color in autumn.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SciAm_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SciAm-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Sometimes the hunters are also placed in the firmament, represented by the stars of the Big Dipper's handle.\n</p><p>The original prototype of the myth must have been invented at least 15,000 years ago for it to have diffused across the <a href=\"/wiki/Beringia\" title=\"Beringia\">Bering land bridge</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-d&#39;Huy_2013_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-d&#39;Huy_2013-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsect